\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid15670295 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15670295 NARRATIVE OF A WOMAN WHO WAS EIGHTEES YEAHS ALONE, UPON THE ISLAND OF SAN NICOLAS, COAST OF CALIFORNIA
\par 
\par Mr. EDITOR :(--)It is with pleaaure
 that I have seen your efforts to rescue from oblivion, and perpetuate in your Magazine, the many wonderful things that relate to the early history of our State. During a residence of eight years upon this coast, in which time I have explored over eightee
n
 hundred miles of it, I have been enabled to treasure up many things in my journal which may be of interest to your many readers; I shall take pleasure in occasionally giving you an extract from it, an, as there is no time like the present, I will commenc
e with the following:
\par 
\par Alexander Selkirk, the hero of Defoe's enchanting story of Robinson Crusoe, was only four years upon the desert island of Juan Fernandes. {\*\atrfstart 415666242}
Could we but find an author at the present day, with Defoe's graphic imagination, we believe suf
ficient facts of the lonely exile of this woman for eighteen years, could be obtained to make one of the most thrilling and beautifully descriptive volumes ever published.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid7633252 
{\*\atrfend 415666242}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 415666242}{\*\atndate -1490490047}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid7633252 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7633252 Girl Crusoe}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15670295 
\par 
\par Those who are acquainted with the geography
 of the coast, will remember that about two hundred and fifty miles south of San Fnulcisco, a chain of islands commences, called the Santa Barbara Islands. While stationed upon one of this group(--)the islaod of San Miguel(--)making tidal observations for
 
the U. S. Government, I was visited by Mr. George Nediver, an old resident of California, who came over from the main land, on a hunting excurson, and encamped beside me, and from whom I obtained much valuable information concerning the early history of t
hese islands, as well as the adjacent coast. 
\par 
\par One evening, while seated beside our quiet camp-fire, placidly smoking our pipes, Mr. N. related to me the following remarkable history :
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 415666243}Twenty years ago, the whole of the Indian tribes inhabiting this group 
of islands were engaged in a fierce and exterminating war with each other, and to sUch an extent waa this deadly hostility waged that already the population had very much diminished, and would, in all probability, before many years, become entirely extinc
t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid16522950 {\*\atrfend 415666243}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 415666243}{\*\atndate -953705541}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid16522950 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16522950 Indians as savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15670295 
. To prevent this, and at the same time to ameliorate the condition of the Indians, the good Fathers of the Mission of Santa Barbara conceived the idea of removing them to the main land, where they might be watc
hed over, improved, and preserved, under their immediate superintendance.
\par 
\par For this purpose they visited the islands, in company with a few partially civilizcd Indians, and explained to them the advantages of removing to the Miasion. They listened attentiv
ely to the proposal, and finally consented to go, on promises of protection from their natural enemies being given by the Fathers.
\par 
\par Accordingly a small vessel was sent to the different islands, and the various tribes were taken one by one, to the Mission o
f Santa Barbara. But while the last of the Indians were embarking, at the island of San Nicolas, and all were supposed to be on board, a child was missing, and its mother, in great distress was seeking everywhere, without success ; each portion of the ves
sel was diligently searched ; all the adjacent rocks were examined, but no child could be found. Almost frantic, the mother requested the Capttain to wait while she went into the interior to search for her child, to which he reluctantly consented.
\par 
\par As night
 closed down in darkness, heavy masses of clonds rolled up from the horizon, and gave threatening evidence of a coming storm. All were anxious for the return of the woman and her child, before it broke upon them, but still they came not. The wind began to
 
blow, harder and stronger ; the storm was rapidly increasing : and as the groups of Indians on board strained their eyes, trying to discover, in the darkness, some object that resembled the returning woman and her child, yet saw them not, there were many 
sad hearts and anxious countenances that night, on their account.
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 415666244}The storm at last came on in all its fury, tossing their little vessel up and down like a feather, and compelled them at last, though reluctantly, to put to sea for safety, before any tiding
s of the absent ones could be received; and, although the cargo of living freight reached Santa Barbara in safety, before the vessel could return for the woman, it Was wrecked and entirely lost ; and as no other could be obtained at that time, the poor wo
man had to remain upon the island, where she lived, <i>alone</i>, for eighteen years ; no doubt forgotten, or given up as long since dead.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid16522950 {\*\atrfend 415666244}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor 
Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 415666244}{\*\atndate -953705536}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid16522950 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16522950 No boat available}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15670295 
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 415666245}After the discoery of gold, it was r[um]ored that San Nicolas was inhabi
ted, and this, no doubt, had its foundation in the fact that several hunters of the sea otter, had seen the print of human footsteps, and they endeavored to discover the whereabouts of the individuals, but could not : yet, as all the footprints were alike
,
 they concluded that there could be only one person living upon it ; and many attempts were made to find out who, and where this strange being was, but without avail, until one of California's oldest pioneers, Mr. Nediver(--)the gentleman who related to m
e
 the story, and who arrived in this country some twenty-five years ago, and still resides at Santa Barbara(--)went over to look for her, and who, having spent many years as a hunter, and trapper in the Rocky Mountains, was as expert as an Indian, in follo
wing a trail, and consequently found but little difficulty in discovering the track, which he followed until he saw a singular object among the rocks upon the sea shore, near the mouth of a ravine, upon its knees, engaged in skinning a seal. 
{\*\atrfstart 415666246}Upon approachin
g, he found it to be a woman clad in a singular dress of feathers ; and, when she saw him, she jumped up, and with excessive joy ran towards him, and seemed almost beside herself with wild delight, at the eight, once more, of a human being.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
